normal'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US"> </span></h1>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></h1>
</div>
<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_1._Introduction" id="_1._Introduction"></a><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">1. Introduction</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
 style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Sri Lanka</span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">, formally
known as Ceylon, is a multi-ethnic and multi-religion island nation in the Indian
Ocean, near the southern coast of India. The distance between the south-eastern
tip of India and north-western Sri Lanka is only about 40 miles. Sri Lankaâs total land area is 25,330 square miles, roughly the size of West Virginia, and it a
population of a little more than 20 million. Due to major civil conflict that
has affected Sri Lanka for more than two decades, no census was conducted in
certain parts of the country during the last two decades or more. Thus, all
demographic figures include relevant estimates for certain areas in the
country. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The ethnic and religious
diversity of the nation, and also its colonial history, have a direct bearing
on aspects of the legal system of Sri Lanka.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The countryâs largest
ethnic group is the Sinhalese whose native tongue is the Sinhala language. The
Sinhalese form about 74% of the population. The majority of the Sinhalese are
Buddhists, with a Christian minority. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The next largest ethnic
group is composed of the Tamils who form 18% of the population, and their
native tongue is the Tamil language. The majority of the Tamils are Hindus,
with a Christian minority. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The majority of the
Christians among both the Sinhalese and the Tamils are Roman Catholics. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The descendants of
Indian tea-estate workers, brought in by the British from Southern India from
the nineteenth century to the 1930s, form a distinct group. Their native
language also is Tamil and they also are referred to as up-country Tamils. The
majority of up-country Tamils are Hindus, and they still form a mainstay of the
tea industry employees. The 18% figure for the percentage of Tamils in Sri Lanka includes the up-country Tamils.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The third largest ethnic
group is composed of Muslims, mainly descendants of Arab traders, and Malays,
mainly descendants of South-East Asians who arrived in Sri Lanka during Dutch rule of the country. For a significant segment of the Muslims, Tamil is the
main language. The Muslims, excluding the Malays, constitute about 7% of the
population. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The other ethnic group
is composed of Burghers who are descendants of Dutch and Portuguese settlers,
and are mostly Christian. Largely due to the strongly nationalist politics that
began in the 1950s, a significant segment of the Burghers emigrated to Australia. Due to this emigration, and also due to Burghers marrying Sinhalese and Tamils,
the Burghers now are a relatively small community in Sri Lanka. English is the
first language for the Burghers. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The
Burghers, Malays, and the Veddhas, who are the descendants of the original
inhabitants of Sri Lanka, form about 1% of the population. (All
ethnic-composition figures are from the &quot;<i>New York Times Almanac</i>&quot;
2008).</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_2._Colonial_History" id="_2._Colonial_History"></a><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">2. Colonial
History and the Law</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">European control of what
is now Sri Lanka began a few years after 1505 when inclement weather drove a
Portuguese fleet of ships, commanded by Lourenco de Almeida, into what is now
the Colombo harbor. Colombo, now the capital of Sri Lanka, is on the west coast
of Sri Lanka. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Almeida, who also
realized the strategic value of the island-nation in the context of trade
routes, established cordial relations with the King in Kotte. Over a few years
the Portuguese, capitalizing on the divisions within the Kotte kingdom,
gradually gained control of much of the countryâs coastal regions. Kotte,
situated in a suburb of Colombo, is now the legislative capital of Sri Lanka.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Portuguese did not
introduce their laws in the coastal regions they controlled. They did, however,
establish the Roman Catholic faith as the strongest Christian faith in the
country.Â  The Portuguese were ousted by the Dutch during the 1600s.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">With the Dutch gaining
control of Sri Lanka, primarily in the coastal regions, Roman-Dutch law gained
a presence in the country. This âRoman-Dutch law has withstood many a tide of
legal and political change to remain as the foundation of Sri Lankaâs general
and common law.â <sup><a href="#One"><span style='text-decoration:none'>1</span></a><a
name="oneone" id="oneone"></a></sup></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Dutch judicial
system was well organized. Three major courts of justice were established: one
each in Colombo (west), Galle (south), and Jaffna (north). A circuit court, the
Land Raad, presided over by a dissava, sat in various districts. Local chiefs
sat in on cases involving local customs.Â  Thus the customary and personal laws
that existed in the West, South and North of the country also were administered
in the courts, unless these were in sharp discord with Dutch jurisprudence. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The customary and
personal laws are based on ancient customs of the Sinhalese and Tamils whose
ancestors hailed from specific regions in the country, as well as the customs
of the Muslims. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">In the 18<sup>th</sup>
century, Roman-Dutch law was increasingly used in the south-west and the south.
As a consequence, private property (land) rights spread rapidly in these areas,
and property transfers were subject to Roman-Dutch law. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Dutch also made
efforts to codify the customary law of the different ethnic groups.Â  Codifying
Sinhala customary law, however, posed difficulties because of regional diversity
and associated issues. Partly as a consequence of this problem, Roman-Dutch law
increasingly applied to the Sinhalese in the coastal areas, especially to those
Sinhalese who were Christians. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The <i>Thesawalamai</i>,
the laws and customs of the Tamils of the Northern Jaffna province, was
codified in 1707. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">A code of Muslim law was
applied with the consent of Muslim elders.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The British ousted the
Dutch from Sri Lanka in 1796, and adopted a unitary administrative and judicial
system for the entire country. A decision by the British to continue enforcing
the existing laws, and consequent developments, led to Roman-Dutch law gaining
a firm presence in the entire country. As the Sri Lankan legal academic Anton
Cooray states: </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">âThe surrender of the
Dutch possessions in Sri Lanka in the twilight years of the Eighteenth Century
was a blessing in disguise for the future of Roman-Dutch law (in Sri Lanka).â <sup><a href="#Two"><span style='text-decoration:none'>2</span></a><a
name="twotwo" id="twotwo"></a></sup></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">In 1815, when the Kandyan Kingdom in central Ceylon fell to the British, for the first time in history, the
entire country of Ceylon came under the rule of a foreign power. At this point,
the application of Roman-Dutch law was extended to the whole country: âThe
British administration, which undertook to continue to apply existing laws,
extended the application of Roman-Dutch law beyond the Dutch controlledÂ 
coastal areas when, in 1815, British sovereignty extended to the whole of Sri Lanka.â <sup><a href="#Three"><span style='text-decoration:none'>3</span></a><a
name="threethree" id="threethree"></a></sup></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><sup><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></sup></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The British established
a modern system of judicial and civil administration. They respected the
prevailing laws, namely the Roman-Dutch laws, and the customary laws that
applied to the different ethnic groups.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='margin-left:36.0pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:
-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">British
rule lasted through 1948, when Sri Lanka gained its independence.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_3._Legal_Constructs" id="_3._Legal_Constructs"></a><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">3. Legal
Constructs</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Under British rule, the
Charter of Justice of 1801 ensured the continuation of the laws that were in
force at that time.Â  These applicable laws were all of the following:
Roman-Dutch principles brought into force by the Dutch, the <i>Kandyan Law</i>
that applied to the Kandyan provinces, the <i>Thesawalamai Law</i> (also spelt
as âTesawalamaiâ) that applied to the Jaffna Tamils in the Jaffna province, the
Muslim Law that applied to the Muslims, and a limited body of Buddhist and
Hindu Law applicable mainly to Buddhist and Hindu religious property and
customs. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">This conglomeration of
different laws led to British judges encountering some difficulty in
ascertaining applicable laws, especially where Roman-Dutch law principles were
expected to be followed. As a consequence, on many occasions British judges
introduced principles of English law on the basis that there existed ambiguity
on the applicability of Roman-Dutch law. The lack of judicial precedents, and
the un-codified nature of the laws, provided an excuse for judges to avoid applying
Roman-Dutch law principles. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">As a consequence, a body
of English law principles was in force along with Roman-Dutch law, in addition
to indigenous laws such as Kandyan Law and Thesawalamai. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Roman-Dutch Law</span></b><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US"> now
generally applies in Sri Lanka when statutes and indigenous laws do not
regulate the issue in question. Roman-Dutch Law represents in Sri Lanka an inherited legal tradition. It has co-existed with several systems of indigenous laws,
and the English common law, creating a âdistinct legal culture that is
described today as a âmixedâ civil and common law system.â<sup><a href="#Four"><span
style='text-decoration:none'>4</span></a><a name="fourfour" id="fourfour"></a></sup></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><sup><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></sup></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Thus âRoman-Dutch law is
often described in Anglo-American legal terminology as the âcommon lawâ of Sri Lanka â¦ A system of law that applies in Sri Lanka when statutes and indigenous laws do not
regulate any matter.â<sup><a href="#Five"><span style='text-decoration:none'>5</span></a><a
name="fivefive" id="fivefive"></a></sup></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">In fact, when the
British themselves declared Roman-Dutch law as the common law of Ceylon, Roman-Dutch law assumed even greater importance under the British than it had enjoyed under
Dutch rule of Ceylon. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Today, Roman-Dutch law
exists only in Sri Lanka and South Africa. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Kandyan Law</span></b><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US"> applies to
ethnic Sinhalese whose can trace their lineage back to the Kandyan provinces
during the period of the Kandyan monarchy in central Sri Lanka. The Kandyan
monarchy ceased to exist with the British takeover of central Sri Lanka in 1815.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Kandyan Law does not
apply to all Sinhalese who are now resident in the Kandyan provinces; however, Kandyan
Law does apply to Kandyan Sinhalese who now do not reside in the Kandyan
provinces in central Sri Lanka.Â  Kandyan Law that remains applicable to Kandyan
Sinhalese in present day Sri Lanka relates to marriage, divorce, and interstate
succession.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Kandyan Sinhalese have
the option of choosing to marry under the <i>Marriage and Divorce</i> <i>(Kandyan)
Act</i>, or the <i>General Marriage Ordinance</i>. Kandyan Sinhalese who choose
to marry under the <i>Kandyan Act</i> will be governed by Kandyan law in
matters relating to marriage, divorce and interstate succession by virtue of
the <i>Kandyan Law</i> <i>Ordinance</i>, as well as the <i>Kandyan Matrimonial
and Inheritance Ordinance. </i></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><i><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></i></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Kandyan laws on adoption
are also applicable to those who marry under Kandyan Law. The General Law
applies in other related issues such as alimony and child custody. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Kandyan Sinhalese who
choose to marry under the <i>General Marriage Ordinance</i> are governed by
Roman-Dutch Law in matters relating to marriage, divorce, and interstate
succession.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><i><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></i></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The relevant laws on
this topic are mostly in the<i> Kandyan Declaration and Amendment</i> <i>Ordinance</i>,
and the <i>Kandyan Marriages and Divorce<b> </b>Act</i>. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></b></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Theswalamai Law</span></b><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US"> is based on
ancient customs of Jaffna Tamils in Sri Lanka. It applies to Tamil inhabitants
of the Jaffna Peninsula in Northern Sri Lanka. This customary and personal law
also applies to numerous Jaffna Tamils who no longer live in the Jaffna Peninsula. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">It is a commonly held
belief among many in Sri Lanka that Thesawalamai applies only to Jaffna Tamils
who reside in the Jaffna peninsula. The Supreme Court of Sri Lanka, however,
ruled in a 1988 case, <i>âSivagnanalingam v. Suntheralingam</i><sup><a
href="#Six"><span style='text-decoration:none'>6</span></a></sup><a
name="sixsix" id="sixsix"></a> that <i>Thesawalamai </i>is a personal law that applies to
Jaffna Tamils wherever they live in the country, and that it applies also to
their movable and immovable property, wherever it is situated in the country.
The Supreme Court, overturning decisions of the lower courts, held that <i>Thesawalamai</i>
would not apply to Jaffna Tamils only if there is âunequivocal evidence of
abandonment ofâ¦inhabitancy in Jaffna.â</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">This Supreme Court ruling
suggests that a Jaffna Tamil could live for decades in another part of the
country and not lose âJaffna inhabitancyâ if he or she, for instance, continues
to own property in the Jaffna Peninsula, or even visits Jaffna on a somewhat
regular basis. The ruling also indicates that each case must depend on its own
facts.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The only <i>Thesawalamai</i>
laws that are now applicable to Jaffna Tamils relate to property and interstate
succession resulting from marriage.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><i><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></i></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><i><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Thesawalamai, </span></i><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">which was
codified by the Dutch in 1706, gained legal validity when the British enacted
the <i>Thesawalami Regulation No. 18 of 1806</i>. Other relevant laws are <i>Ordinance
No. 5 of 1869</i>, the <i>Matrimonial Rights and Inheritance Ordinance<b> </b>of</i>
<i>1911</i>, amended <i>by Ordinance No. 58 of 1947</i>, The <i>Thesawalamai
Ordinance</i> and <i>Thesawalamai Pre-Emption Ordinance</i>, and the <i>Jaffna
Matrimonial Rights and<b> </b>Inheritance Ordinance No.1 of 1911.</i></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">In Family Law related
issues, the <b>Muslim Special Laws</b> apply to all Muslims in Sri Lanka. When a Muslim marries another Muslim, the bride and the groom do not have the
option of getting married under the General Law, unlike in the case of Kandyan
Sinhalese. Marriage, divorce and other related issues involving Muslims are
governed by the <i>Marriage and Divorce (Muslim) Act, no.13 of 1951</i>, and
any subsequent amendments. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Issues related to
interstate succession and donations, involving Muslims, are dealt with under
the <i>Muslim Interstate Succession Ordinance No.10 of 1931</i>, and any
subsequent amendments. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">There is awareness now
that these personal and customary laws based on ancient customs discriminate
against women. As the Supreme Court pointed out in <i>Sivagnanalingam v.
Suntheralingam</i>, under <i>Thesawalamai</i> âthe surviving spouse is not
(automatically) an heir of the deceasedâs estate.âÂ  The spouse, however, has
preferential claim under certain circumstances. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Also, under Muslim
personal laws, for instance, âAlthough section 25 (1) (b) of the <i>Muslim
Marriage and Divorce Act</i> states that the consent of the bride is essential
to a marriage, in reality her presence is not required when the marriage
contract is concluded between the father or guardian of the bride, and the
groom. The consent of the bride is irrelevant to the conclusion of the marriage
contract.â<sup><a href="#Seven"><span style='text-decoration:none'>7</span></a><a
name="sevenseven" id="sevenseven"></a></sup></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The efforts needed to
revise these personal laws based on ancient customs, in order to remove any
bias against the rights of women, are now hindered by the debate over minority
rights in Sri Lanka:</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Given
the context of a war [the current ethnic conflict in Sri Lanka], whose
rootsÂ Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  belong to
ethnic tensions, it is unlikely that we would see in the next few years </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  amendments
to the personal laws which would result in positive change forÂ Â  </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  [womenâsÂ 
rights]. This is because the concept of womenâs right to equality has</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  been
continuously subordinated in Sri Lanka to the major debate on minority </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  rights. <sup><a
href="#Eight"><span style='text-decoration:none'>8</span></a><a
name="eighteight" id="eighteight"></a></sup></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">It should be pointed
out, however, that these types of personal laws notwithstanding, only a
minority of women to whom these laws are applicable suffer undue
discrimination. In 1960, Sri Lanka elected the worldâs first woman Prime Minister,
Sirimavo Bandaranaike. Bandaranaikeâs daughter, Chandrika Bandaranaike
Kumaratunga, was elected President twice (under a different Constitution).
Kumaratunga served as President from 1994 to 2005.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">An authority on Sri
Lankan law, H.W.Tambiah, touches on the rich and complex nature of Sri Lankan
law:</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  In Sri Lanka, there are five systems of private law. The Roman-Dutch law, asÂ Â Â  </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  modified by
statutes, and interpreted by the courts, is the general law of the land. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  English
common law applies to commercial contracts and commercial property </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  and has been
tacitly accepted in many matters. English law was also introduced</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  by statute
and as such forms the statutory law of the land. The Thesawalamai is </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  both a
personal and local lawâ¦. Similarly, Kandyan Law applies to the Kandyan</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â  Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Sinhalese,
and the Muslim laws, to the Muslims, in [matters relating to] marriage, </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  divorce,
[alimony] and inheritance.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Private law
governs issues between individuals. It consists of the law of persons,</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  property,
obligations, and delicts or torts. <sup><a href="#Nine"><span style='text-decoration:
none'>9</span></a><a name="ninenine" id="ninenine"></a></sup></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_4._The_Structure" id="_4._The_Structure"></a><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">4. The
Structure of the Courts System</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The court-structure
consists of a Supreme Court, a Court of Appeal, High Courts, Municipal Courts,
and Primary Courts. Additionally, there are numerous tribunals, etc. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">In cases involving
criminal law, a Magistrateâs Court or a High Court is the only court with
primary jurisdiction; the respective legal domains of each are provided in the <i>Code
of Criminal Procedure.</i>Â  </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The preponderant majority
of criminal law cases are initiated at a Magistrateâs Court. These cases may be
initiated by any police officer, or public servant, with a written or oral
complaint to the magistrate (see section on Magistrateâs Court). </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Murder trials and
various offenses against the State originate in a High Court (see section on
High Courts). </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Original jurisdiction
over most civil matters lies with the relevant District Court (see section on
District Courts). </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Until 1972, The Judicial
Committee of the Privy Council in Britain was the final court of appeal for Sri Lanka. The right of appeal to the Privy Council âwas abolishedâ¦as there were concerns
that any attempt to discard the existing Constitution in 1972 might be adjudged
unconstitutional.â <sup><a href="#Ten"><span style='text-decoration:none'>10</span></a><a
name="tenten" id="tenten"></a></sup></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">At that time,
âParliamentarians constituted themselves as members of what was termed the
âConstituent Assemblyâ to draft and adopt a new Constitution,â <sup><a
href="#Eleven"><span style='text-decoration:none'>11</span></a></sup><a
name="eleveneleven" id="eleveneleven"></a> which became effective on May 22, 1972. It has been
suggested that the concerns of minority communities in Sri Lanka were not adequately considered in the drafting of that Constitution. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">On Aug 31, 1978, another
Constitution replaced the 1972 Constitution. Under this Constitution, for the
first time in Sri Lanka an Executive President, elected by the entire country,
became the leader of the country.Â  Under the earlier Constitution, the
government was headed by a Prime Minister, who, as a Member of Parliament,
would have been elected by just one electorate in the country.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">As a consequence of
major civil strife that erupted in 1983, now efforts are being made to replace
the 1978 Constitution with a new Constitution in order to grant greater
political autonomy to the different regions in the country. These efforts, at
present, seem stalled in an All Party Conference constituted by the current
President, Mahinda Rajapakse. Furthermore, not all political parties in the
country agreed to participate in the Conference.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">There are also other
courts such as the Kathi Courts that handle matrimonial disputes among Muslims,
and numerous tribunals (see section on Other Courts). </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_4.1_The_Supreme" id="_4.1_The_Supreme"></a><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">4.1. The Supreme Court</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Supreme Court is the
highest and final court of record, and exercises final civil and criminal
appellate jurisdiction.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Litigants who do not
agree with a decision of the original court, be it civil, criminal, or Court of
Appeal, may take the case before the Supreme Court, with permission from the
Court of Appeal, or special permission from the Supreme Court. The Supreme
Court, however, will only agree to consider cases involving a substantial legal
issue.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Supreme Court is
composed of a Chief Justice and not less than six, and not more than ten, other
judges.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Cases that fall under
the several jurisdictions of the Supreme Court are exercised, subject to
provisions in the Constitution, by a bench of at least three judges of the
Supreme Court.Â  Thus different cases may be heard at the same time by several
judges of the Supreme Court sitting apart.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Constitution
provides the Chief Justice with the authority to increase the number of Supreme
Court judges hearing a particular case to five or more judges. This increase in
the number of judges hearing a Supreme Court case would transpire especially if
the issue under consideration is one of general and public importance. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Appeals of decisions of
a High Court Trial at Bar are heard by a Bench of five or more Supreme Court
judges.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Supreme Court is
entrusted with certain exclusive jurisdictions. Subject to provisions in the
Constitution, the Supreme Court exercises jurisdiction over constitutional
matters and fundamental rights issues.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Also, the Supreme Court
exercises sole and exclusive jurisdiction over questions concerning the
constitutionality of a parliamentary bill or a particular provision in the
bill, subject to certain constitutional requirements. The Supreme Court has the
exclusive jurisdiction to hear and determine issues relating to the
interpretation of the Constitution.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Supreme Court also
has the sole and exclusive jurisdiction to hear and determine issues relating
to the infringement of fundamental rights by Executive or Administrative
action. These fundamental rights include freedom of thought, conscience and
religion; freedom from torture; right to equality; freedom from arbitrary
arrest, detention and punishment; prohibition of retroactive penal legislation;
and freedom of speech, assembly, association and movement.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Constitution
provides for temporary restrictions on fundamental rights if national security
issues are involved.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><i><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></i></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Supreme Court also
exercises consultative jurisdiction. If the President of the Republic deems
that a question of law or fact that has arisen is of such a nature and of such
public importance, the President may refer the question directly to the Supreme
Court for an opinion.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The consultative
jurisdiction also extends to any concerns expressed by any Member of Parliament
regarding the ability of the President to effectively discharge his or her
duties. These concerns, in the first instance, would be addressed in writing to
the Speaker of the House of Representatives by the member or members of
Parliament. These concerns would be that the President is permanently incapable
of discharging the functions of the office due to mental or physical frailty,
or that the President is guilty of intentional violation of the Constitution,
treason, bribery, misconduct or corruption involving the abuse of the powers of
the Office of President, or any offense under any law involving moral turpitude.
</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">When the Speaker,
subject to specific requirements in the Constitution, refers the allegations to
the Supreme Court, the Court is required to report its findings to the Speaker
within two months. During the Supreme Courtâs determination of the issue, the
President can appear before the Court to present his or her case, or the
President may be represented by an attorney-at-law. The Supreme Court then
reports its determination, and the reasons for its determination, to the
Parliament.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">This determination and
opinion of the Supreme Court should be by at least five judges of the Supreme
Court, including the Chief Justice, except for in the event of the Chief Justiceâs
recusal. The Chief Justiceâs recusal will result in another judge of the Supreme
Court taking the Chief Justiceâs place.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Based on the Report from
the Supreme Court, the Parliament may vote to remove a President from office,
subject to specific requirements in the Constitution.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Supreme Court also
exercises jurisdiction over legal issues related to the election of a President
of the country, and legal issues surrounding a referendum. The Constitution
stipulates that the foregoing two issues have to be determined by a bench of at
least five Supreme Court judges, including the Chief Justice, unless the Chief
Justice appoints another Supreme Court judge in his or her place.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Legal issues surrounding
any breach of privileges of Parliament by any person also fall under the
purview of the Supreme Court.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Supreme Court cases are
published in the <i>Sri Lanka Law Reports</i>. As of October 2008, Supreme
Court cases from 1878 through 2005 are accessible online. See the section on
Cases, Bills and Acts. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Judges of the Supreme
Court and Court of Appeals (next section) are appointed by the President of the
Republic, subject to provisions in Article 41C of the Constitution. Article 41C
was introduced by the 17<sup>th</sup> Amendment to the Constitution which
became effective on October 3, 2001. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The 17th Amendment
stipulates that the Presidentâs selection and appointment of a Supreme Court
judge requires the approval of the Constitutional Council, which is composed of
the Prime Minister, the Speaker of the Parliament, the Leader of the Opposition
in Parliament, a nominee of the President, five persons appointed by the
President who were nominated by both the Prime Minister and the Leader of the
Opposition, and one person selected by the majority of Members of Parliament
belonging to political parties or independent groups not affiliated with the
political parties or groups of the Prime Minister or Leader of the Opposition.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Constitutional
Councilâs approval is not required if the appointment is for a period of less
than 14 days.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">An order of the
President of the Republic is required to remove from office a Supreme Court judge,
including the Chief Justice. The Presidentâs order for removal of a judge is
preceded by the President addressing the Parliament on the relevant issues
surrounding the âproved misbehavior, or incapacity,â that necessitates the
removal of the judge from office. The removal of a Supreme Court judge requires
the support of a majority of the Members of Parliament, including those members
not present in Parliament at the time of the vote.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Speaker of the
Parliament will agree to the Presidentâs address to Parliament if not less than
one-third of the Members of Parliament sign a notice of the resolution in
support of the Presidentâs address to Parliament. The notice of the resolution
will provide the full particulars of the alleged âmisbehavior,â or the incapacity
of the judge to carry out the functions of a Supreme Court judge.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Parliament, by law
or by Standing Orders, provides for all matters relating to the presidential
address to Parliament, including the procedure for passing the resolution,
information on the investigation, proof of the alleged âmisbehaviorâ or
incapacity of the judge, and the right of the judge to appear before Parliament
and be heard in person or through a representative.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The age of retirement
for Supreme Court judges is 65 years. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></b></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_4.2_Court_of" id="_4.2_Court_of"></a><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">4.2. Court of Appeal </span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Court of Appeal is
the first appellate court for decisions of all original courts and certain
Tribunals. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Court of Appeal is
composed of the President of the Court, and not less than six, and not more
than eleven other judges. Many cases at the Court of Appeal are presided over
by a single judge. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Court of Appeal
hears appeals against judgments of the High Courts.Â  It exercises appellate
jurisdiction for the correction of errors in fact or in law at a High Court, or
any Court of first instance, or Tribunal, or other Institution.Â  In addition to
the jurisdiction to affirm, reverse, correct, or modify a judgment, the Court
of Appeal may give directions to a Court of first instance, Tribunal, or other
Institution, or order a new trial, or order additional hearings as the Court of
Appeal deems appropriate. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">âEven when there is no
right of appeal from a particular court or tribunal, [the Court of Appeal] can
exercise [its] powers ofÂ  ârevisionâ and quash the original courtâs or
tribunalâs order [based on] an error of law apparent [in] the record.â <sup><a
href="#Twelve"><span style='text-decoration:none'>12</span></a></sup><a
name="twelvetwelve" id="twelvetwelve"></a> The Court of Appeal, if appropriate, also has the
authority to issue a âstay orderâ and suspend proceedings in a lower court
until the revision application is heard and determined.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Court of Appeal also
has the authority to receive and admit new evidence additional, or
supplementary, to evidence already recorded in a court of first instance.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Appeals of judgments,
sentences and orders at a High Court Trial at Bar are forwarded directly to the
Supreme Court by virtue of the <i>Code of Criminal Procedure (Amendment)</i> <i>Act,
No.21 of 1988.</i></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><i><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></i></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Court of Appeal, in
exercising its power to examine and reverse a judgment of any court of first
instance, has the authority to examine any record of any court of first
instance. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Court of Appeal also
exercises the power to grant and issue, as provided by law, writs of
certiorari, prohibition, procedento, mandamus, and quo warranto. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Court exercises
jurisdiction to grant writs of habeas corpusÂ  in order to bring before the
Court a person who has to be dealt with according to the law, or to bring
before the Court a person illegally or improperly detained in public or private
custody.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Court of Appeal grants
injunctions, and also exercises the jurisdiction to try petitions challenging
the election of a Member of Parliament.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Court of Appeal sits
in Colombo, the Capital city. The Chief Justice may direct that particular
sittings of the Court be held in another judicial zone or district. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Appeals against
judgments, sentences and orders of the High Court (other than judgments,
sentences and orders delivered at a Trial-at-Bar), are heard by at least two
judges of the Court of Appeal.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Parliamentary election
petitions are heard by the President of the Court of Appeal, or by a judge of
the Court of Appeal nominated by the President of this Court, or by more judges
of the Court of Appeal nominated by the President of this Court, of whom the
President of the Court may be one. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Other issues before the
Court may be heard by a single judge of the Court of Appeal.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">If the Court hearing a
case consists of two judges and they fail to agree on a decision, the issue is
reviewed by three judges of the Court of Appeal.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Court of Appeal cases
are now published in <i>Sri Lanka Law Reports</i>. As of October 2008, Court of
Appeal cases from 1809 through 2005 are accessible online. See section on
Cases, Bills, and Acts. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The appointment of Court
of Appeal judges requires the same procedure as that for the appointment of
Supreme Court judges (see earlier section on the Supreme Court). The age of
retirement for Court of Appeal judges, however, is 63, as opposed to 65 for Supreme
Court judges.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The removal from office
of a Court of Appeal judge requires the same procedure as that for the removal
of a Supreme Court judge, with the President of the Republic addressing
Parliament and a majority of the Members of Parliament, including those not
present in Parliament, supporting the removal (See the three paragraphs
preceding the final sentence in the Supreme Court section.)</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_4.3_High_Courts" id="_4.3_High_Courts"></a><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">4.3. High Courts</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Trials at a High Court
are conducted by the State (Sri Lanka), through the Attorney-Generalâs
Department. The Attorney-Generalâs Department prosecutes on behalf of the
State.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Murder trials and
various offenses against the State are tried at the High Court; other criminal
offenses are tried at a Magistrateâs Court. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">While some High Court
trials will have a jury, some trials will not have a jury. The types of cases
that require a jury are provided in the <i>Second Schedule of the Judicature
Act</i> <i>No.2 of 1978</i>. Also, the Attorney-General has the authority to
determine whether a case that does not fall into a category provided in the <i>Second
Schedule of the Judicature Act</i> <i>No.2 of 1978</i> should nonetheless have
a jury.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Penal Code
stipulates the types of cases argued in a High Court: âThe Penal Code defines
most of the criminal offenses known to our law. And the <i>Code of Criminal</i>
<i>Procedure Act. No: 15 of 1979</i> sets out which of these offenses [can be
tried] by each court [High Court and Magistrateâs Court].â <sup><a
href="#Thirteen"><span style='text-decoration:none'>13</span></a><a
name="thirteenthirteen" id="thirteenthirteen"></a></sup></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The High Court is
composed of not less than ten and not more than forty judges. This Court sits
in 16 provinces in the country (16 High Courts).</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The High Court of each
province exercises:</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">i.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Â Original
jurisdiction over prosecution of offenses committed within a particular
province. </span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">ii.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Admiralty
jurisdiction, which is usually exercised in Colombo, the capital city. </span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">iii.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Commercial
jurisdiction, which is vested by the High Court of the Provinces (Special
Provisions) Act, No. 10 of 1996.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">iv.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Jurisdiction
to hear cases involving attempts to influence the outcome of a decision made,
or an order issued, by the Judicial Service Commission. This jurisdiction is vested
by Article 111 L (2) of the Constitution.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">v.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Applications
for the return of, or access to, a child, under the Hague Convention, is
handled by the High Court of the Western Province (<i>Civil Aspects of
International Child</i> <i>Abduction Act, No:10 of 2001</i>).</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">vi.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Appellate
jurisdiction over convictions, sentences, and orders imposed by the
Magistrateâs Courts and Primary Courts within the province. </span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">vii.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Writ
jurisdiction in respect to powers exercised under any law or statutes enacted
by the Provincial Council of that particular province, with regard to an issue
delineated in the Provincial Council List.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">viii.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Appeals
of decisions reached by Labor Tribunals, Agrarian Tribunals, and Small Claims
Courts.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Provincial High
Court sits in the following cities: Colombo, Kalutara, Galle, Matara,
Batticaloa, Jaffna, Chilaw, Negombo, Gampaha, Kegalle, Kurunegala, Kandy, Avissawella, Ratnapura, Badulla, and Anuradhapura. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Judges of the High Court
are appointed by the President of the Republic on the recommendation of the Judicial
Service Commission, and in consultation with the Attorney-General. The
President of the Republic, acting on the advice of the Judicial Service
Commission, exercises authority in disciplinary matters concerning the High
Court judges. The President may terminate the service of a High Court judge on
the advice of the Judicial Service Commission.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Judicial Service
Commission (JSC)<b> </b>was established by the enactment of Article 111D of the
Constitution, incorporated by the 17<sup>th</sup> Amendment, which became effective
on October 3, 2001. The JSC is composed of the Chief Justice (as Chairman) and
two other judges of the Supreme Court appointed by the President of the
Republic. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></b></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The age of retirement
for High Court judges is 61.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_4.4_District_Courts" id="_4.4_District_Courts"></a><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">4.4. District
Courts</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">District Courts are the
Courts of first instance for civil cases. District Courts have jurisdiction
over all civil cases not expressly assigned to the Primary Court or a
Magistrateâs Court. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
  style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Sri Lanka</span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US"> has 54
judicial districts. Every District Court is a court of record and is vested
with unlimited original jurisdiction in all civil, revenue, trust, insolvency
and testamentary matters, other than issues that are assigned to any other
court by law.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Certain specific civil
issues handled by the District Courts include: </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">i.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Cases
related to ownership of land.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">ii.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Action
by landlords to eject tenants.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">iii.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Action
to recover debts of more than Rs. 1,500.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">iv.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Action
in connection with trademark and patent rights, and infringement of copyright
laws.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">v.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Claims
for compensation of more than Rs. 1, 500 for injuries caused by negligence.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">vi.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Divorce
cases (Formerly, divorce cases were handled by the now defunct Family Courts). </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Commercial disputes that
are more than three million rupees in monetary value fall within the purview of
the High Court in Colombo, the administrative capital, in accordance with the <i>High
Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions), Act No. 10 of 1996</i>.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">There is a standard form
of plaint for each type of action, and if necessary, there may be variations to
the form.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The normal procedure is
for the filing of a plaint by the plaintiff.Â  The plaint is argued before a
District Court judge, and if the judge is satisfied that all matters are in
order, an order may be issued to serve summons, along with a copy of the
plaint, on the defendant(s). Usually, the plaintiff, or the plaintiffâs
attorney, must ensure that the Courtâs fiscal officer serves the summons, with
a copy of the plaint, to the defendant.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The defendant appears in
court on the summons returnable date. The defendant, or his or her lawyer, is
provided with a date by which an answer to the plaint is required. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Further pleadings may be
filed, especially if the defendant files a counter-claim, a claim in
reconvention.Â  The counter-claim, if any, must relate to the issue brought
before the District Court by the plaintiff. The plaintiff may then file a
replication in response to the defendantâs claim in reconvention. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The above procedure is
the normal procedure at the District Court. There is also a Summary Procedure
for the District Court provided in Chapter 53 of the <i>Civil Procedure</i> <i>Code</i>.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Judges of the District
Courts are appointed by the Judicial Service Commission (See section on High
Courts for information on the JSC). The JSC has the power to dismiss and
maintain disciplinary control over the District Court judges.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The retirement age for
District Court judges, generally, is 60 years.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_4.5_Magistrate&rsquo;s_Courts" id="_4.5_Magistrate&rsquo;s_Courts"></a><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">4.5.
Magistrateâs Courts</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Magistrateâs Courts
are established under the <i>Judicature Act, No.2 of 1978.</i></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Each Judicial division
has one Magistrateâs Court, and there are 74 judicial divisions in Sri Lanka. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Each Magistrateâs Court
is vested with original jurisdiction over criminal offenses (other than
offenses committed after indictment in the High Court.)</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">In cases involving
criminal law, the Magistrateâs Courts and the High Court are the only Courts
with primary jurisdiction. The respective domains of these Courts are detailed
in the <i>Code of Criminal Procedure.</i></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Appeals from these
courts of first instance may be made to the Court of Appeal and, under certain
circumstances, to the Supreme Court, which exercises final appellate
jurisdiction.Â  </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The vast majority of the
nationâs criminal cases are tried at the Magistrateâs Courts level, which forms
the lowest level of the judicial system. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Cases may be initiated
at a Magistrateâs Court by any police officer or by anyone else making an oral
or written complaint to the Magistrate. The Magistrate is empowered to make an
initial investigation of the complaint, and to determine whether his or her
Court has proper jurisdiction over the matter, whether the matter should be
tried by the High Court, or whether the matter should be dismissed. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">If it is determined that
the Magistrateâs Court has the proper jurisdiction over the matter, the prosecution
may be conducted by the complainant (plaintiff), or by an officer of the
Government, including the Attorney-General, the Solicitor-General, a state
counsel, or any officer of any national or local government office. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">At the trial, the
accused has the right to call and cross-examine witnesses. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Trials are conducted
without a jury, and the verdict and sentence are given by the Magistrate.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Any party in a case who
is in disagreement with a judgment has the right to appeal the judgment, on any
point of law or fact, at the Court of Appeal.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">If the police decide not
to institute criminal proceedings in a Magistrateâs Court, the complainant has
the option of filing a private plaint, and the complainant may retain an
attorney for this purpose.Â  </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">As indicated earlier,
while murder trials and various offenses against the State (Sri Lanka) are tried in a High Court, other criminal offenses are tried in a Magistrateâs
Court. The Penal Code defines which court, a Magistrateâs Court or a High
Court, has the necessary jurisdiction (<i>Code of Criminal Procedure Act No.15
of 1979</i>).</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">If a new offense is
codified by law, for instance the <i>Prevention of Terrorism Act</i>, the
relevant statute will indicate the manner of trial.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Magistrateâs Courts
are ordinarily empowered to impose the following sentences: A fine of up to Rs.
(rupees) 1,500.00, and/or two years of rigorous or simple imprisonment, unless
special provisions vest the Magistrateâs Courts with the power to impose higher
penalties.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Magistrates are
appointed by the Judicial Service Commission (JSC), and the Commission
exercises disciplinary oversight over the judges, including the power of
dismissal (See section on High Courts for information on the Judicial Service
Commission).</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The retirement age for
Magistrateâs Court judges, generally, is 60 years.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_4.6_Primary_Courts" id="_4.6_Primary_Courts"></a><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">4.6. Primary
Courts</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Each Primary Court is
vested with the following jurisdictions:</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">i.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Original
civil jurisdiction over cases involving debt, damages, demands, or claims that
do not exceed Rs. 1,500.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">ii.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Enforcement
of by-laws by local authorities and disputes relating to recovery of revenue by
these local authorities. </span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">iii.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Exclusive
criminal jurisdiction over cases relating to offenses âprescribedâ by
regulation by the Justice Minister.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">iv.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Offenses
in violation of the provisions of any Parliamentary Act, or subsidiary
legislation, that is related to jurisdiction vested in the Primary Courts.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The Primary Courts are
established under the <i>Judicature Act, No.2 of 1978.</i></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">There are seven Primary
Courts:Â  One each in Anamaduwa, Angunukolapelessa, Kandy, Mallakam, Pilessa,
Wellawaya and Wennappuwa. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">In all other divisions,
the Magistrateâs Court exercises the jurisdiction of the Primary Courts. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Requests for revision of
orders made by a Primary Court are handled by the High Court in that province.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">All Primary Court judges
are appointed by the Judicial Service Commission (JSC), which is also vested
with the power of dismissal of the Primary Court judges (See section on âHigh
Courtsâ for information on the JSC).</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Generally, the
retirement age for Primary Court judges is 60.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_4.7_Other_Courts" id="_4.7_Other_Courts"></a><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">4.7 Other
Courts and Tribunals</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The other courts include
the Kathi Court, the special tribunal that adjudicates on matrimonial matters
relating to Muslims. Buddhist ecclesiastical matters that fall under the
purview of the <i>Buddhist Temporalities Ordinance of 1931</i> are heard by the
ordinary courts. Disciplinary matters pertaining to Buddhist clergy are handled
by religious councils which are under the authority of the Buddhist priests
themselves. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">There are numerous administrative
tribunals, such as the Inland Revenue Board of Appeal, The Workmenâs
Compensation Tribunals, Labor Tribunals, the Board of Appeal under the
Factories Ordinance, Tribunals under Agricultural Productivity Law, Labor
Tribunals under the Wages Board Ordinance, etc. </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Most decisions of these
tribunals can be appealed at the Court of Appeal; when regarding a substantial
question of law, the decision of the Court of Appeal may be taken up at the
Supreme Court.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_5._Case_Law" id="_5._Case_Law"></a><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">5. Case Law</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The principle of <i>stare
decisis </i>is adhered to in Sri Lanka.Â  Supreme Court decisions are binding on
all other courts. A decision of the Court of Appeal is binding on the courts of
first instance, if the decision is not in conflict with a decision of the
Supreme Court. Since 1978, when a new Constitution became effective in Sri Lanka, decisions of the Supreme Court before 1978, and the decisions of the Privy Council when
this Council in the U.K. was the final Court of Appeal for Sri Lanka, are technically no longer binding. But the earlier case law may still serve as âguidance,â
and the word âguidanceâ suggests that the earlier case law is much closer to
binding evidence than to persuasive evidence.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
  style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Sri Lanka</span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">âs laws
passed before 1978 remain valid through <i>Article 168</i> of the 1978 Constitution.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_6._Cases,_Acts," id="_6._Cases,_Acts,"></a><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">6. Cases, Acts, and
Bills</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Supreme Court and Court
of Appeal cases now are published in the <i>Sri Lanka Law Reports</i>. As of
October 2008, Supreme Court cases from 1878 through 2005, and Court of Appeal
cases from 1809 through 2005 are accessible online </span><span lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US"><a
href="http://www.commonlii.org/databases.html#region:asia"><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;text-decoration:none'>here</span></a></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">.Â  Access
this link and then scroll down to the Asia section and select the Sri Lanka link. There also is a link at this site for Sri Lanka legislation. The
legislation-link, however, may not download quickly.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">Acts and Bills of
Parliament, when available for publication, are published in the </span><span
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US"><a href="http://documents.gov.lk/"><i><span style='font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;text-decoration:none'>Extra Gazette</span></i></a></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">. The Acts
and Bills links are at the top left corner of this site. Usually, it takes a while
for the Acts, Bills, Forms, Gazette, and News links to appear on the top left
corner. After accessing the Acts or Bills link, select the âEâ link for
English. The âSâ link is for the Sinhala language version, and the âTâ link is
for the Tamil language version.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></h1>

<h1 style='text-align:justify'><a name="_7._Major_Codifications" id="_7._Major_Codifications"></a><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;'
lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">7. Major
Codifications</span></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></b></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The major codifications
are:</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style='text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">i.<span
style='font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">The
Civil Code.</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style='margin-left:72.0pt;text-align:justify;
text-indent:-36.0pt'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:&quot;Georgia&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;' lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">ii.<span
